  <p><alert>Problem Set</alert> </p>

 <exercise>
 <p>
                When we introduce a third axis, we can divide our space into 8 octants. 
                For each octant, give an example of a point that solely lies within that octant
                (no boundary points!) For reference,
                 <url href="https://davidmathlogic.com/amit/octants.html" visual="this"/>
                 can be used to visualize the different octants and you can check your work using
                 <url href="http://www.math.uconn.edu/~dnichols/amit/pointplotwithinput.html" 
                 visual="this applet"/>. 
</p>
</exercise>

<exercise>
    <p>  Use <url href="https://davidmathlogic.com/amit/vectoraddition.html" visual="this applet"/> to visualize 
                    adding the vectors  <m>\lt -7, 5 \gt </m> and <m> \lt 4, 3 \gt </m>. 
                    Which property is <url href="https://davidmathlogic.com/amit/vectorcommutivity.html" 
                    visual="this applet" /> 
                     demonstrating about vector addition? What other properties does vector addition have? 
 </p>
</exercise> 

<exercise>
    <statement>

    <p>
        Use <url href=" https://davidmathlogic.com/amit/vectorcomponents.html" visual="this applet" /> to help visualize our vector components. 
        Draw the vector <m> \lt 3, -4, 5 \gt </m> using the applet and upload your picture to your homework. 
        </p>
    </statement>
</exercise>

<exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
         <url href="\href{https://davidmathlogic.com/amit/unitvector.html" visual="This applet" />  
         provides a nice visualization of the relationship of the unit vector and the process of normalization. 
         <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                 Write at least one sentence describing what you notice about 
                    the relationship between vectors, normalization, and unit vectors demonstrated by this applet. 
                </p>
            </li>
             <li>
                <p>
                Use the applet to find a unit vector in the direction of <m> \lt 4,-3,1 \gt </m>.
                    </p>
            </li>
         </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
</exercise>

<exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Experiment with <url href=" https://davidmathlogic.com/amit/projections.html" visual="this applet" /> 
            which visualizes projections. Attach 3 different pictures of projections onto the 
            same vector <m>\mathbf{a}</m>. What patterns do you see (with respect to direction, length, etc.)?
        </p>
    </statement>
</exercise>

<exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
             The following applets demonstrate calculating a dot product and cross product.
              Calculate the dot product and cross product for <m> \mathbf{u} </m> and <m> \mathbf{v} </m>,
               <m> \mathbf{u} </m> and <m> \mathbf{w} </m>, <m> \mathbf{v} </m> and <m> \mathbf{w} </m>, 
               and <m> \mathbf{w}  </m> and  <m> \mathbf{v} </m> for <m> \mathbf{u}= \lt 2, 7, -3 \gt, </m>
             <m>   \mathbf{v}= \lt 0, -1, -2 \gt, </m> and <m> \mathbf{w}=\lt -1, 1, 6 \gt </m> using the applets:
                <url href="https://davidmathlogic.com/amit/dotproduct3d" visual="dot product applet" /> and
                <url href="https://davidmathlogic.com/amit/crossproduct.html" visual="cross product applet" />.
              What is a property you notice which is true for dot products but not cross products?
        </p>
    </statement>
</exercise>

<exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            We can use dot products and cross products to calculate a volume of a parallelepiped. Use the applet to draw the parallelepiped and calculate 
            its volume using <url href="https://davidmathlogic.com/amit/parallelepiped.html" visual="applet" />.
        </p>
    </statement>
</exercise>
